f the highest percentages in Europe of overweight or even obese children, and this is linked both to a change – worrying – of food habits and to the poor propensity of Italians to physical activity. Much must be invested strategically in the culture of prevention (individual and collective) and in the awareness of opportunities but also of the limits of modern medicine. Much, therefore, can and must be done on the organizational level, but the real emergency is to adapt the financing of Ssn to the standards of advanced European countries (8% of GDP), and is urgent and indispensable, because a Ssn that works not only health protection but also contributes to social cohesion".
